 some RE of your own.</div><br /><br />- Not really, but what's the problem if <em>YES</em>? Are you against the use of test ROMs somehow? Unfortunately, I'm unable to build a dev-kit for reasons I won't discuss here.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">If you are only interested in running existing games perfectly and passing all existing tests, it seems like you don't care about making the emulator actually accurate, you just want a certificate saying it is so.</div><br /><br />- Man, you're being harsh. Nope, I don't. Once again, what's wrong with testing?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Personally, I don't like its UI that much either. It's slightly more responsive and better designed than the one in ..., but still a bit annoying. I've actually switched to bsnes as my primary SNES emulator, I like it as much as I like Nestopia for the NES.<br /><br />The UI is the least important thing though, IMO. If an emulator has other features to compensate for it (accuracy, debugging tools, etc), I'll take whatever UI it has to offer.</div>
