	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Bah, that was really poorly worded, sorry. I was trying to say that they're not appropriate for improving accuracy as a whole, as in for the entire scene and everyone else's emulators. Meaning you can implement them, but you haven't made something that's better than existing emulators.
<br />
<br />Of course if the test ROMs verified a behavior and you passed it, that would make your emulator more accurate. Assuming of course you didn't implement it wrong while still getting a pass result. That's one of the big limitations of test ROMs. The person making them understands the entire situation, but may not necessarily catch every "wrong" case. Thus, the person making the test ROM is more likely to pass it the correct way than anyone else.
<br />
<br />For instance, I may write a decimal-mode overflow flag test, but I can't really test all 4 billion combinations of 16-bit registers, so I test the corner cases. I spent weeks working on it so I know all about how decimal-mode and overflow works, but you're simply trying to get a pass or fail and trying random things until success. So you mess up 0+1 due to some subtle bug.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


