	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">byuu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I had to try about 20 more things, ruling out every possibility, before I found out what was really wrong and got it fixed properly.</div><br />And at that point, when you discover what's going on, you need to document it and make a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_testing" class="postlink">regression test case</a> so that you can find the problem if it rears its head again.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Development of an emulator that doesn't target those hardware restrictions and limitations creates a tiny square that is much <em>more</em> forgiving than the real thing.</div><br />Early on in the development of VisualBoyAdvance, I noticed a few differences between the hardware and the emulator where the emulator was more forgiving. I did a bit of RE and wrote a test case that would pass on hardware and fail on a more forgiving environment like VBA. I think I made at least half a dozen of these and posted them to gbadev. Sure, what any test suite measures is measuring is "compatibility" with the test suite, but as the coverage of the test suite grows, "compatibility" with the test suite becomes a better and better predictor of "accuracy", which itself cannot be measured.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">There does actually seem to be a good subset of users who really love completely custom UIs for their uniqueness over their function. You can see that with Genecyst, ZSNES and RetroCopy for instance.</div><br />Genecyst and ZSNES use a custom GUI toolkit because they run (or first ran) on MS-DOS, which has no GUI library and therefore no chance for "platform integration". The Linux and Windows ports keep the custom toolkit for a consistent look and feel across all supported platforms, much like Swing in Java.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">It may not look pretty, but nothing beats platform integration for usability.</div><br />I acknowledge the value of platform integration at 60 cm when you're investigating a technical defect in your emulator or your game. But where a custom UI shines is for general use, such as play testing: you're sitting <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/10-foot_user_interface" class="postlink">2 m or more away</a> from your home theater PC's TV-sized monitor and you expect to be able to operate the UI with a game controller or an infrared remote. Compare Front Row on the Mac to the ordinary iTunes interface, for example.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Initialization is the worst: often times it's random, but randomness is an emulator breaks testing, breaks movie playback, breaks netplay, etc etc.</div>
<br />Even Internet lag breaks netplay. I noticed the controls for LJ65 became a lot more slippery when I tried to play it over Kaillera.

		

