	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I did a bit of RE and wrote a test case that would pass on hardware and fail on a more forgiving environment like VBA.</div><br /><br />That's true, tests can be made in the opposite direction just as easily. I even have a few like that for VRAM writes and such.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">But where a custom UI shines is for general use, such as play testing: you're sitting 2 m or more away from your home theater PC's TV-sized monitor and you expect to be able to operate the UI with a game controller or an infrared remote.</div>
<br />
<br />You can get pretty close. Allow a stylesheet that can add * { font-size: 20pt; } to get the font readable. Now map the load cartridge shortcut to a gamepad button, have a file loader that responds to the D-pad arrows for navigation, and buttons to load.
<br />
<br />What we really need though is OS-level integration of gamepads as first-class input devices. Minimize to what we really need:
<br />- menu access button (eg Alt)
<br />- control navigation (eg Tab)
<br />- select button (eg Spacebar)
<br />- arrows keys (D-pad)
<br />
<br />And perhaps as a slower alternative:
<br />- mouse movement (thumbstick)
<br />- mouse left+right (buttons)
<br />
<br />In theory, one could write such an app that can monitor the gamepads and send virtual key/mouse events to other applications. I wonder why no one has done this.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


