	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Litmus tests are too arbitrary. As I've said, I don't think any (S)NES emulator is accurate. I don't think there's a concept of "accurate" as a boolean attribute. It's all relative. Emulator A can be more accurate than Emulator B, but that doesn't make either accurate or either inaccurate.
<br />
<br />And again, 98% of people don't care about accuracy at all. They care that it plays their favorite games, that it's easy to use, and perhaps most importantly, that it was the first tool they used.
<br />
<br />Example: I wrote xkas v06 as an SNES cross assembler, it was the first tool of its kind publicly distributed. But it was a terrible tool that I wrote in a single day, and it shows. I went back and spent two weeks writing xkas v12 -- it is better in every possible way, but everyone uses v06 instead. Because it was the first one out there.
<br />
<br />Another example is IPS vs UPS. IPS is a pathetically inferior format in every single possible way, but it's what caught on first. Not even any bias, IPS excels at <em>nothing</em>. Bigger patch sizes, limited to 16MB, can't unpatch, can't verify patches, can't detect copier headers, includes potentially copyrighted data directly, has three different post-spec extensions that are supported differently by each tool, and on and on. Yet everyone loves it.
<br />
<br />Nestopia got popular because NESticle may as well have been DOS only, was discontinued, and because it was much more accurate, really awesome in terms of features, and was at the right place at the right time; when people were looking to go from DOS to Windows for their emulator needs.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


